  <!-- Frequently Asked Questions -->
  <section class="py-24 bg-white border-t border-neutral-100">
    <div class="container mx-auto px-4 md:px-8 max-w-4xl">
      <div class="text-center mb-16">
        <h2 class="text-base font-bold text-primary-600 uppercase tracking-widest mb-4">Tree Removal FAQs</h2>
        <p class="text-4xl font-bold font-heading text-neutral-900">Common South Carolina Questions</p>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-4">
        <!-- FAQ 1 -->
        <details class="group bg-neutral-50 rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 [&_summary::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
          <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between p-6 md:p-8 text-neutral-900 font-bold text-xl">
            Do I need a permit to remove a tree in South Carolina?
            <span class="transition duration-300 group-open:-rotate-180 text-primary-600 bg-white p-2 rounded-full shadow-sm">
              <ChevronDown size={24} />
            </span>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-6 md:px-8 md:pb-8 text-neutral-600 leading-relaxed mt-2">
            Permit requirements vary by municipality. For example, Charleston strictly protects "Grand Trees" (24+ inches DBH), while Greenville and Columbia have their own landscape ordinances. We handle all local permit applications to ensure your tree removal is 100% legal and compliant.
          </div>
        </details>

        <!-- FAQ 2 -->
        <details class="group bg-neutral-50 rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 [&_summary::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
          <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between p-6 md:p-8 text-neutral-900 font-bold text-xl">
            How can I tell if my oak or pine tree is diseased?
            <span class="transition duration-300 group-open:-rotate-180 text-primary-600 bg-white p-2 rounded-full shadow-sm">
              <ChevronDown size={24} />
            </span>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-6 md:px-8 md:pb-8 text-neutral-600 leading-relaxed mt-2">
            Common SC tree issues like Oak Wilt, Oak Leaf Blister, or Southern Pine Beetle infestations often present as thinning canopies, early leaf drop, or sawdust at the trunk base. If you notice these signs, contact us for a professional health assessment.
          </div>
        </details>

        <!-- FAQ 3 -->
        <details class="group bg-neutral-50 rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 [&_summary::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
          <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between p-6 md:p-8 text-neutral-900 font-bold text-xl">
            Does homeowners insurance cover tree removal?
            <span class="transition duration-300 group-open:-rotate-180 text-primary-600 bg-white p-2 rounded-full shadow-sm">
              <ChevronDown size={24} />
            </span>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-6 md:px-8 md:pb-8 text-neutral-600 leading-relaxed mt-2">
            If a tree falls on a covered structure (like your house or fence) due to a storm, your insurance typically covers the removal cost. We work directly with local SC insurance adjusters to streamline your claim process.
          </div>
        </details>

        <!-- FAQ 4 -->
        <details class="group bg-neutral-50 rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 [&_summary::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
          <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between p-6 md:p-8 text-neutral-900 font-bold text-xl">
            What do you do with the wood and stump?
            <span class="transition duration-300 group-open:-rotate-180 text-primary-600 bg-white p-2 rounded-full shadow-sm">
              <ChevronDown size={24} />
            </span>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-6 md:px-8 md:pb-8 text-neutral-600 leading-relaxed mt-2">
            We offer comprehensive cleanup. We can haul all debris away, chip the branches into landscape mulch, or leave the wood cut to firewood length. We also provide professional stump grinding so you can replant immediately.
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
      
      <div class="text-center mt-12">
        <p class="text-neutral-500 mb-6">Have more questions about your specific tree?</p>
        <a href="/contact/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 bg-primary-600 text-white px-8 py-4 rounded-md font-bold hover:bg-primary-700 transition-colors shadow-lg">
